A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The Electronic Warfare Integrated Reprogramming (EWIR) program element hosts the Department of War (DoW's) first System of System Technology Integration Tool
Chain for Heterogeneous Electronic Systems (STITCHES) project. STITCHES is a fully government developed, owned, maintained, and open-source Modular Open
Systems Architecture (MOSA) toolchain and multi-classification information system that creates new capabilities by integrating incompatible DoW fielded systems and
architectures together without the need to modify system source code. STITCHES' separable and community-based databases allow disparate teams across the DoW
to utilize STITCHES in separate security levels without co-mingling data. The STITCHES project utilizes the STITCHES Warfighter Application Team (SWAT) at Cyber
and Networks (C&N) PEO, Special Programs Divisions, Kill Chain Branch (AFLCMC/HNJJ) as an integration team employing, maintaining, and instructing other teams
in the DoW how to use the STITCHES integration platform. AFLCMC/HNJJ will utilize the STITCHES interoperability software on systems both within and external to
AFLCMC/HNJJ and deploy and maintain the capabilities created to the requesting organizations. The Program Management Office (PMO) interfaces and integrates
with other DoW systems and their authorities to support DAF missions and lead MAJCOM directed activities. The PMO is responsible for testing, maintaining, and
deploying STITCHES generated interoperability into DoW systems supported by AFLCMC/HNJJ, working with existing DoW test and certification organizations such as,
but not limited to, the 46th Test Squadron, 613th Air Operations Center, and the Marine Corps Tactical Systems Support Activity, and teaming with organizations outside
of AFLCMC/HNJJ when adapting and creating novel system of systems using capabilities from these organizations. The PMO will deliver adaptive and cutting-edge
electromagnetic spectrum capabilities that provide the warfighter a tactical and strategic competitive advantage and freedom to attack, maneuver, and defend.

 The PMO shall leverage the prime contractors to provide mission support as directed, including establishing a software development team composed of a government
 tiger team, the STITCHES toolchain developer, a secure cloud infrastructure and repository developer, and mission partners. The PMO includes a revolving team of
 subsystem subject matter experts when adapting DoW systems using STITCHES. The PMO is responsible for the execution of tasks employing STITCHES outlined in
 NDAA 2021 Section 804 and supports Joint All Domain Command and Control (JADC2) tasking and integration efforts in support of JADC2.

 The PMO will conduct regular STITCHES training courses to scale the capability to the DoW. The PMO may team with other DoW organizations utilizing STITCHES to
 increase the scale of the deployed capabilities.

 The STITCHES integration platform achieved a Cross Domain Solution (CDS) Authority to Operate (ATO) prior to the DoW's Raise the Bar (RTB) certification
 requirement process. The STITCHES integration platform will be submitted to the National Cross Domain Strategy and Management Office (NCDSMO) for Cross
 Domain Solution certification in FY27.

 This program integrates DoW systems together to create new EW/EMSO capabilities and conducts prototyping activities on emerging and enabling technologies to
 inform future EMSO capabilities. This program utilizes the software acquisition pathway.

