A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
This program creates new EW/Electromagnetic Spectrum Operations (EMSO) capabilities and conducts prototyping activities on emerging and enabling technologies to
enable future EMSO app based reprogramming capabilities, waveform development, and EMSO assessments.

 Tactical Application Pipeline (TACAPP) Development/Deployment Strategy. TACAPP is a premier cloud-based application that will expedite the delivery of software
 solutions directly to the warfighter. To posture the Air Force for agile Cloud-based rapid reprogramming capability by creating the Production and Pre-Production release
 management lifecycles for applications/Mission Ware and supporting software-defined capability systems release for NIPR, SIPR, and SAP environments. Creating
 the infrastructure and technology to enable the Mission Ware and software capability within the 350SWW, and management processes to facilitate the rapid capability
 delivery mechanism necessary for agile EMBM planning and execution. Application and Mission Ware development, V&V, and delivery thru TACAPP are vital to the
 success of the 350 SWW mission to provide a rapid capability delivery and management to the warfighter. This capability will be critical to providing rapid reprogramming
 to F-35, F-22, C-12, EC-130H/EA-37B COMPASS CALL, RJ, E-3 as well as B-21, F-47, CCA, and other 5th/6th gen platforms.

 Open System Architecture (OSA) and Post-Flight Data Analysis (PFDA) driven waveform development against novel threats. In alignment with the 350 SWW mission
 directive, the program applies in-house expertise and the government-owned OSA frameworks (such as Big Iron Software Framework (BISF)) to address Intel and PFDA
 informed EMSO targets/threats. The core objective is to conduct adversary EW vulnerability analysis to develop, test, and validate organic, platform-agnostic waveforms.
 These solutions are engineered to fill critical mission needs for the warfighter, directly impacting LRKC effects. This effort is foundational to achieving operational
 integration with CCMD, Air Component, and MAJCOM plans and exercises, ensuring the developed capabilities are relevant and effective in contested environments.
 Funding is essential for the engineering, development, and technical support and infrastructure required to fulfill the 350 SWW's mandate. This effort will support the
 adversary EW vulnerability analysis/target development and the subsequent design, build, and validation of EW solutions using the OSA, PFDA, and other internal tools.

 Develop and deploy EMSO Assessments strategy. Execute COMBAT SHEILD EW Assessments, and develop, administer, and continually assess organizational
 and large force EW capabilities inherent in our combat platforms. The intended end state is to achieve an increased level of fidelity and scope of assessed own-force
 EW criteria, enabling the USAF to gain and maintain a clear, decisive advantage over our adversaries within the EMS. This effort provides critical feedback to force
 providers, developers, and warfighters on the operational readiness of their systems in a contested electromagnetic environment. Funding is required for the technical
 expertise, analytical tools, and test infrastructure necessary to conduct rigorous



