 Beginning in FY 2026, all MQ-9 RDT&E funding transitioned to PE 1160403BB, Aviation Systems, Project SF100: Aviation Systems Advanced Development, to support
 the acceleration of the A2E concept.

 The FY 2026 spend plan amount for Aviation Systems includes $126.378 million of discretionary and $105.546 million of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of
 $231.924 million.

 SF100 Aviation Systems Advanced Development:
 This project provides for the development, rapid prototyping, demonstration, and integration of current and maturing technologies for Special Operations-peculiar
 (SO-p) aviation and training requirements to transform the foundation of future SOF aviation for the Joint Force. Timely application of SO-p technology is critical
 and necessary to meet requirements in areas such as: Aviation Engineering Analysis (AEA); Electronic Warfare (EW)-Radio Frequency Countermeasures (RFCM);
 MH-47G and MH-60M SOF Common Terrain Following (TF)/Terrain Avoidance (TA) Silent Knight Radar (SKR); Precision Strike Package (PSP), Medium Altitude Long
 Endurance Tactical (MALET) MQ-9, and the Adaptive Airborne Enterprise (A2E). The AEA provides engineering analysis, market research, and designs to address
 aircraft survivability needs such as signature management, situational awareness, and versatile mission platform/equipment (payloads, communication, and weapons)

