INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0401134F$$, 2027, $$The Large Aircraft Infrared Countermeasures (LAIRCM) system is an evolutionary acquisition program designed to provide significantly improved defensive systems
capability for Department of War (DoW) aircraft to counter the man-portable air-defense systems (MANPADS) and other surface-to-air Infrared (IR) missile threats. It is
now being upgraded with new detection capabilities to provide aircrew with awareness of laser warning, small arms fire, rocket-propelled grenades, anti-aircraft fire, and
laser guided munitions, with new sensors entering production in FY 2029.

 The LAIRCM system configuration consists of missile warning sensors (MWS), a laser transmitter assembly, control interface unit, and processors to detect, track, jam,
 and counter incoming missiles. The system is currently installed on 54 aircraft types and over 1,200 aircraft. The program's baseline development is complete. However,
 new efforts are required to continue addressing and countering new and emerging threats. The system is fully autonomous following the system power-up. LAIRCM
 requirements are documented in the multi-command Operational Requirements Document (ORD) LAIRCM ORD 314-92, validated on 03 Aug 1998.

 The baseline development program is complete. Follow-on efforts continue Evolving Threat Analysis in order to address and counter new and emerging threats, as well
 as ensure integration onto new aircraft types and existing LAIRCM platforms. Additional efforts include design changes to improve reliability, maintainability, & availability
 and system improvements with form, fit, function and interface compliant replacements.

 In FY 2027, the Air Force's focus is to expand protection of large aircraft beyond the threats LAIRCM counters.
portfolio to pivot and transition LAIRCM into the Large Aircraft Survivability System (LASS) program in FY 2027. To achieve this, the Air Force adjusted the lines of effort
 in PE 0401134F, LAIRCM, to be 1) Evolving Threat Analysis (ETA), 2) Long Range Detect, 3) Active Detection, and 4) Advanced Defeat Technologies to help restore
 and rebuild capability for Survivable High-Value Airborne Assets.

 Latent Capability Development (LCD) is intended to update the LAIRCM system to defend against unique threats. In FY 2027, PE 0401134F, LAIRCM, Project 67A037,
 LCD, was transferred to PE 0401334F, Large Aircraft Survivability Systems (LASS), Project 67A038, Active Defense Sensor. This funding provides programmatic
 support to update the system, to include hardware, software, and firmware, to enable the system's ability to detect and defeat a distinct category of threats and update to
 the latest threat models. Development begins at the AFRL Dynamic Infrared Missile Evaluator (DIME) Lab before transitioning to Northrop Grumman Corporation (NGC)
 for inclusion into the LAIRCM software baseline.

 The Active Defense Sensor (ADS) provides sensing and cueing of threats, which is anticipated to employ a version of a long-range Radio Frequency (RF) defense
 sensor to provide long range sensing and cueing of threats. In FY 2027, efforts under PE 0401134F, Project 67A038, Active Defense Sensor, were transferred
 to PE 0401334F, Large Aircraft Survivability Systems (LASS), Project 67A038, Advanced Sensors. ADS will enhance existing High Value Airborne Asset (HVAA)
 survivability to detect and employ new tactics against an expanded category of threats. Anticipated efforts include, but are not limited to: hardware and software upgrade,
 development, and integration; prototyping; testing of the sensor as it integrates into a modular system of systems approach to maintain defensive capability against new
 and emerging threats.

 This requirement supports performance of a full financial audit as required by title 10 U.S.C. Chapter 9A, Sec 240-D.

 This program element included all necessary expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such program funds would be in
 addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 0605829F, 0605831F, 0605833F, and 0605898F.

 This program is in Budget Activity 7, Operational System Development because this budget activity includes development efforts to upgrade systems that have been
 fielded or have received approval for full rate production and anticipate production funding in the current or subsequent fiscal year.
Operational Systems Development$$, $$The Large Aircraft Infrared Countermeasures (LAIRCM) system is an evolutionary acquisition program that provides significantly improved defensive systems capability
for DoD aircraft to counter the man-portable air-defense systems (MANPADS) missile threat. The system is currently installed on 54 aircraft types and over 1,200
aircraft.

 The current LAIRCM system configuration consists of missile warning sensors (MWS), a laser transmitter assembly, control interface unit and processors to detect,
 track, jam and counter incoming missiles. The number of sensors and transmitter assemblies per aircraft is determined by the size and signature of the aircraft. The
 system is fully autonomous following system power-up. LAIRCM requirements are documented in the multi-command LAIRCM Operational Requirements Document
 (ORD) 314-92, validated on 03 Aug 1998.

 The Active Defense Sensor (ADS) will provide sensing and cueing of threats, which is anticipated to employ a version of a long-range Radio Frequency (RF) defense
 sensor to provide long range sensing and cueing of threats. ADS will enhance existing High Value Airborne Asset survivability to detect and employ new tactics against
 an expanded category of threats. Anticipated efforts include, but are not limited to hardware and software upgrade, development, and integration; prototyping; testing of
 the sensor as it integrates into a modular system of systems approach to maintain defensive capability against new and emerging threats.

 In FY 2027, the Hostile Fire Indication/Laser Warning (HFI/LW) efforts were transferred from Project 674942, LAIRCM to Project 67A038, Active Defense Sensor to
 continue the development of capabilities for the LAIRCM system. ADS continues development of the Multi Threat Mid-Wave (MW) Infrared (IR) Sensor, a new MWS for
 the LAIRCM system. The Multi-Threat MW IR sensor will increase the effectiveness of the LAIRCM system by providing aircrews with enhanced detection capabilities
 against small arms fire, rocket-propelled grenades, anti-aircraft fire, and laser-guided munitions.

 This program element included all necessary expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such program funds would be in
 addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 0605829F, 0605831F, 0605833F, and 0605898F.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                         FY 2025          FY 2026        FY 2027
Title: Active Defense Sensor                                                                                                                       -             7.529             -

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
Description: Active sensor that receives a cue from the Long Range Detect Sensor (LRDS) then locates a potential threat and
generates range information. It maintains custody of the target until the processor validates it as a real threat. The ADS then
provides the processor with the necessary range data to determine the optimal launch time for an effector. Following launch, the
ADS guides the effector by transmitting coordinates and range information, a process that requires it to continuously send and
receive signals from both the effector and the target to ensure a successful engagement. This will significantly increase situational
awareness for operators and provide the high-fidelity data necessary to update threat models, ensuring they accurately account
for new and emerging adversary capabilities.

FY 2026 Plans:
Award multiple Other Transaction Agreement (OTA) prototype development agreements and begin sensor development,
maturing the system for physical demonstration. This involves hardware/software design studies, requirements refinement, sensor
development, implementing modular scalable architecture, and conceptual modeling.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Funding decreased due to transfer of Active Defense Sensor development activities from PE 0401134F, LAIRCM, Project 67A038,
Active Defense Sensor, to PE 0401334F, LASS, Project 67A038, Active Defense Sensor.
Title: Multi-Threat Mid-Wave (MW) IR Sensor                                                                                                    -              -       12.323
Description: Development of hardware, software, integration, and test of an upgraded downward looking Multi-threat Mid Wave
(MW) IR sensor to provide new capabilities for aircrew awareness of multiple threats including laser warning, small arms fire, rifle
propelled grenades, anti-aircraft fire, and small un-manned aerial systems (drones). The upgraded sensors are planned to enter
production in FY 2029.

FY 2027 Plans:
Capability upgrade effort with Northrop Grumman to develop improved sensor to enable Hostile Fire Indication/Laser Warning
capabilities including analysis, specification development, planning of all sensor/system development activities, and material
procurement to support test article fabrication.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
funding increase due to transfer of Hostile Fire Indication/Laser Warning (HFI/LW) capability development efforts from Project
674942, LAIRCM, to Project 67A038, Active Defense Sensor.
