INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0804743F$$, 2027, $$Other Flight Training (OFT) program provides systems and data sources for recording and managing aircrew training information, aircrew/parachutist management,
flying hour tracking, flight pay management, and flying gate tracking for over 68,000 Air Force members to enhance safety-of-flight operations and to determine eligibility
to perform aviation related events.

 The OFT program includes the Aviation Resource Tool Enterprise Management Information System (ARTEMIS) effort, an on-line information system for base-level
 Deputy Commanders for Operations. ARTEMIS, which replaced the legacy Aviation Resource Management System (ARMS) that sunset in FY 2025, is a cloud-based
 system providing a common architecture to effectively support the implementation of Air Force flight management policies specified in AFI 11-401 and AFI 11-402. It
 ensures the accurate tracking of flying and ground training programs and delivers real-time analytics and operations management information for aircrew, missileer,
 and parachutist training and readiness. Covering over 68,000 aircrew/parachutists and used by 2,800 1C0X2 Career Field members with 2.2 million transactions per
 week, ARTEMIS provides operations managers with immediate visibility into flying program status, enabling effective resource allocation decisions and robust support
 for weapon systems requirements.

 Funding provides continuing developmental efforts that will focus on both the sustainment and continued development of ARTEMIS to enhance adoption and ensure
 Air Force readiness. Ongoing sustainment activities include minimizing system downtime, resolving escalated issues, maintaining security compliance, improving
 data quality and architecture for enterprise reporting, sustaining integrations with other Operations Enterprise Architecture (Ops EA) initiatives, and executing feature
 enhancements to improve the user experience. Concurrently, developmental efforts will provide additional flying operations information and interface this data into the
 Defense Readiness Reporting System Strategic (DRRS-S). These enhanced capabilities will be developed incrementally and include, but are not limited to, an electronic
 flight record, flying hour management, simulator and Remote Piloted Aircraft (RPA) management, a full career logbook, training look-back, aircrew member man-month
 allocation, enhanced resource and jump module management, and additional interfaces.
addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 0605829F, 0605831F, 0605833F, and 0605898F.

 This program is in Budget Activity 7, Operational System Development because this budget activity includes development efforts to upgrade systems that have been
 fielded or have received approval for full rate production and anticipate production funding in the current or subsequent fiscal year.$$, $$The Aviation Resource Tool Enterprise Mission Information System (ARTEMIS) provides a cloud-based system for recording and managing aircrew training information,
aircrew/parachutist management, flying hour tracking, flight pay management, and flying gate tracking for over 68,000 Air Force members to enhance safety-of-flight
operations and determine eligibility for aviation-related events.

 ARTEMIS, which replaced the legacy Aviation Resource Management System (ARMS) that sunset in FY 2025, is a cloud-based system providing a common
 architecture to effectively support the implementation of Air Force flight management policies specified in AFI 11-401 and AFI 11-402. The migration to the cloud
 environment and the DevSecOps methodology will transform the system to be scalable and flexible, capable of meeting all information requirements of the Aviation
 Resource Management community. It will provide dashboards and data analytics to support decision-making for informing readiness assessments. The cloud
 environment provides the Continuous Integration and Continuous Deployment (CI/CD) pipeline required to constantly deliver software in an agile framework.

 This program ensures the accurate tracking of flying and ground training programs and delivers real-time analytics and operations management information for
 aircrew, missileer, and parachutist training and readiness. Covering over 68,000 aircrew/parachutists and used by 2,800 1C0X2 Career Field members with 2.2 million
 transactions per week, ARTEMIS provides operations managers with immediate visibility into flying program status, enabling effective resource allocation decisions and
 robust support for weapon systems requirements.

 Funding provides continuing developmental efforts that will focus on both the sustainment and continued development of ARTEMIS to enhance adoption and ensure
 Air Force readiness. Ongoing sustainment activities include minimizing system downtime, resolving escalated issues, maintaining security compliance, improving
 data quality and architecture for enterprise reporting, sustaining integrations with other Operations Enterprise Architecture (Ops EA) initiatives, and executing feature
 enhancements to improve the user experience. Concurrently, developmental efforts will provide additional flying operations information and interface this data into the
 Defense Readiness Reporting System Strategic (DRRS-S). These enhanced capabilities will be developed incrementally and include, but are not limited to, an electronic
 flight record, flying hour management, simulator and Remote Piloted Aircraft (RPA) management, a full career logbook, training look-back, aircrew member man-month
 allocation, enhanced resource and jump module management, and additional interfaces.

 This requirement supports performance of a full financial audit as required by title 10 U.S.C. Chapter 9A, Sec 240-D.

 This program element included all necessary expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such program funds would be in
 addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 0605829F, 0605831F, 0605833F, and 0605898F.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                FY 2025      FY 2026      FY 2027
Title: Aviation Resource Tool Enterprise Mission Information System (ARTEMIS)                                                          0.000        2.338        1.950
Description: Software development to update antiquated Aircrew Resource Management System (ARMS) through new
ARTEMIS effort, adding functionality and system interfaces.

FY 2026 Plans:
Sustain and enhance the ARTEMIS platform on Cloud-One to include by not limited to transformation sustainment, data cleansing,
update data mapping and ensure ARTEMIS compliance and integration, and execute backlog enhancement items.
FY 2027 Plans:
Continued update to ARTEMIS platform on Cloud-One. Efforts include but not limited to delivery of software patches to correct
system deficiencies and developmental activities.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Funding decreased due to re-scoping and reduction of planned developmental activities.
                                                                                Accomplishments/Planned Programs Subtotals             0.000        2.338         1.950$$, $$$$, $$The ARTEMIS acquisition strategy employs an evolutionary approach to incrementally develop and field capabilities on its modern, Salesforce-based platform. Initial
development was successfully executed through a partnership with the AF Business Enterprise Systems Programming Innovation (BESPIN) office, utilizing a Section
8a direct award. Current sustainment and continued development are managed through a firm-fixed-price contract, focusing on data usability, integration with the
Operations Enterprise Architecture (Ops EA), and feature enhancements.

 ARTEMIS replaced the legacy Aviation Resource Management System (ARMS) to accelerate the transformation of future "Digital Operations Suite" and future
 acquisition strategy. The program will leverage the Commercial Solutions Opening (CSO) managed by the Secretary of the Air Force, Concepts, Development and
 Management (SAF/CDM) office. The CSO efforts include rapidly acquire and integrate "break-through" commercial technologies, prioritizing innovation over incremental
 improvements and allow ARTEMIS to solicit solutions in key areas like Big Data, AI/ML, and advanced data analytics, attracting a wide range of traditional and non-

 traditional vendors. The CSO provides a streamlined, two-step process (White Paper followed by Proposal) and flexible award types, including Other Transaction
 Agreements (OTAs), which can transition directly to full-scale production contracts. This agile approach lowers barriers to entry for innovators, reduces administrative
 timelines, and ensures ARTEMIS can rapidly evolve to meet the data-driven needs of its 68,000 users and the broader Ops EA ecosystem.

