A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The Aviation Resource Tool Enterprise Mission Information System (ARTEMIS) provides a cloud-based system for recording and managing aircrew training information,
aircrew/parachutist management, flying hour tracking, flight pay management, and flying gate tracking for over 68,000 Air Force members to enhance safety-of-flight
operations and determine eligibility for aviation-related events.

 ARTEMIS, which replaced the legacy Aviation Resource Management System (ARMS) that sunset in FY 2025, is a cloud-based system providing a common
 architecture to effectively support the implementation of Air Force flight management policies specified in AFI 11-401 and AFI 11-402. The migration to the cloud
 environment and the DevSecOps methodology will transform the system to be scalable and flexible, capable of meeting all information requirements of the Aviation
 Resource Management community. It will provide dashboards and data analytics to support decision-making for informing readiness assessments. The cloud
 environment provides the Continuous Integration and Continuous Deployment (CI/CD) pipeline required to constantly deliver software in an agile framework.

 This program ensures the accurate tracking of flying and ground training programs and delivers real-time analytics and operations management information for
 aircrew, missileer, and parachutist training and readiness. Covering over 68,000 aircrew/parachutists and used by 2,800 1C0X2 Career Field members with 2.2 million
 transactions per week, ARTEMIS provides operations managers with immediate visibility into flying program status, enabling effective resource allocation decisions and
 robust support for weapon systems requirements.

 Funding provides continuing developmental efforts that will focus on both the sustainment and continued development of ARTEMIS to enhance adoption and ensure
 Air Force readiness. Ongoing sustainment activities include minimizing system downtime, resolving escalated issues, maintaining security compliance, improving
 data quality and architecture for enterprise reporting, sustaining integrations with other Operations Enterprise Architecture (Ops EA) initiatives, and executing feature
 enhancements to improve the user experience. Concurrently, developmental efforts will provide additional flying operations information and interface this data into the
 Defense Readiness Reporting System Strategic (DRRS-S). These enhanced capabilities will be developed incrementally and include, but are not limited to, an electronic
 flight record, flying hour management, simulator and Remote Piloted Aircraft (RPA) management, a full career logbook, training look-back, aircrew member man-month
 allocation, enhanced resource and jump module management, and additional interfaces.


