Note
In FY2027, funding was transferred within PE 1206616SF, Space Advanced Technology Development/Demo, from Project 63682J, Spacecraft Vehicles to Project
633834, Integrated Space Technology Demonstrations, to align resources in a single Project allowing for streamlined plans to address priority gaps across USSF
mission areas.

A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
This project is a series of advanced technology demonstrations designed to address mission needs by applying emerging technologies from the Air Force Research
Laboratory, other United States government laboratories, and industry. These technologies are integrated into system-level demonstrations that are used to test,
evaluate, and validate the technologies in a relevant environment. This project includes the development and demonstration of programs addressing Department of the
Air Force (DAF) capability gaps.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                            FY 2025          FY 2026     FY 2027
Title: Integrated Satellite Demonstrations                                                                                                        30.374           18.083      21.422
Description: Mature space technology and deliver capabilities that deter war, support the joint all-domain fight, and if called upon,
dominate conflicts in and from space. Advance technologies to enhance timeliness, performance, capacity, agility, and resilience
of US and allied space capabilities for transition to Program Executive Offices and Portfolio Acquisition Executives, and to anchor
future force designs. Perform end-to-end space system technology development and experimentation from ground segment
development to satellite assembly, integration, and test to support multiple Department of the Air Force mission areas. Leverage
first-of-a-kind space system expertise and capabilities to directly support programs across the national security space enterprise,
reduce technical risk, and increase return on investment for emerging operational systems.

FY 2026 Plans:
Continue:
- Efforts to demonstrate technologies for future proliferated systems through small satellite experiments.
- Design, build, and test of small satellite missions with a focus on capabilities in autonomy, cyber resiliency, and integration of
commercial, allied, and government space networks command and control (C2) of a hybrid space architecture.
- Engagement with university partners to design, build, test, and operate satellites in support of risk reduction experiments for
United States Space Force (USSF) missions and to build an experienced workforce for USSF and defense industrial base
employment.

