Title: USSF Integrated Operations Networking (ION)                                                                                                   -             34.703       0.000
Description: ION will provide a secure, reliable, multi-classification transport layer to support space missions. ION will be a
dynamic cloud-based software-defined mission network that integrates Space Force capabilities providing high bandwidth and
low latency for essential capabilities including support to Artificial Intelligence (AI) and the Unified Data Library (UDL). The USSF
Digital Engineering Ecosystem will be integrated into ION. Space Force discovered mission network infrastructure contained
significant technology debt and is initiating ION to better prepare for new threat environment. ION will deploy a SAP, CAP and
IC-capable UDL (UDL-Black) within an accredited government cloud that will enable mission partners to access timely, high
resolution data at all classification levels. The expansion of cloud infrastructure and resilient movement of data are solutions to
gaps in USSPACECOM Offensive Counter Space, Defensive Counter-Space and Integrated Fires Capabilities.

FY 2026 Plans:
FY 2026 efforts will continue to scale and accelerate classified cloud infrastructure expansion in anticipation of projected threat
timelines and expand on the pathfinder implementation to connect disparate, classified space capabilities with an integrated,
resilient data transport network. Expands integration of a secure, reliable, and multi-classification transport layer to include
Command and Control (C2) nodes and incorporates connectivity to the National Space Test and Training Complex (NSTTC)
into the existing classified kill web. Improve classified communications resiliency, integrate development activities, and expand
advanced training and testing opportunities using test & training data sources to improve Space Force's ability to protect and
defend high-priority space missions. Rapidly respond to implement system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to
operate in the contested space domain. Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical
analysis, experimentation, risk reduction, prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S. Government partnership,
and international opportunities to respond to existing and emerging adversarial threats with speed and agility.
