 DEE provides a unified enterprise environment for USSF program offices, operations squadrons, other government stakeholders, and hardware and software vendors,
 enabling responsive, threat-informed product development, testing, deployment, training, mission planning, and on-orbit anomaly resolution. Key capabilities include:
 (1) Connecting multiple Digital Threads—a framework to link all the digital information about a space system, from initial design to operations, into a single, accessible
 system—integrating organizations such as members of the intel community, Space Warfighting Analysis Center (SWAC), and USSF Field Commands to leverage threat
 models for smarter force design, requirements development, solution design, acquisition, and operations planning; (2) Connecting Classified Systems—facilitating
 seamless multi-domain engineering activities across multiple classification levels (e.g., CUI to TS, SCI, SAP); (3) Eliminating Redundant Systems—standardizing tools
 to enhance integration and collaboration; (4) Achieving Cost Efficiencies— reducing costs through enterprise-level capabilities and economies of scale; (5) Enhancing
 Data-Driven Decisions—providing real-time accurate, relevant information for informed leadership decisions; and (6) Supporting Space Force's Digital Transformation
 —providing the applications and environment to advance the Chief of Space Operations' (CSO) vision of the Space Force as a "Digital Service," as outlined in the May
 2021, U.S. Space Force Vision for a Digital Service.
 DEE supports DE by connecting acquisition, test, training, and operational data, models, and activities at the speed of relevance through the delivery of a hybrid cloud
 MLS modeling and data ecosystem. DEE establishes Authoritative Sources of Truth (ASOTs) and Single Sources of Truth (SSOTs) by incorporating data management
 and integration across multiple trusted sources. DEE is designed to connect engineers, program managers, force designers, requirements managers, logisticians,
 developmental and operational testers, training instructors and schoolhouses, operational commanders, senior decision makers, mission partners, industry and
 academia, and all other participants in the Capability Development Lifecycle.

 The DEE is designed to develop, operate, and support integrated information technology (IT), system security, software development, and data/network modernization to
 accelerate and modernize the USSF capability development lifecycle. It equips users with tools to enhance collaboration, user experience, and integration with mission
 partners and industry. DEE helps to assess technical risks posed by adversary threats by analyzing system and enterprise-level risks and incorporates agile software
 practices to scale platforms and infrastructure based on digital thread mission needs. The DEE provides deliberate data exposure and "normalizes” the data to make it
 meaningful and useful for any business or mission use cases.

 The DEE effort includes multiple DEE prototype solutions previously known as the Digital Engineering Integrated Cloud-based Environment (DEICE) Tech Stack. These
 prototypes currently serve as the interim Digital Services Ecosystem (DSE) for USSF Capability Development as a cloud-based, remotely accessible, interconnected
 MLS infrastructure, and provides the technical methodology used to store, access, analyze, and visualize evolving systems' data and models throughout their acquisition
 lifecycles. This project will continue to operate DEICE prototypes with the goal of including or retiring the prototype solutions into the DEE enterprise architecture based
 on their achieved capabilities.

 This program element may include necessary civilian pay expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such program funds
 would be in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 1206392SF and 1206398SF.

 This requirement supports performance of a full financial audit as required by title 10 U.S.C. Chapter 9A, Sec 240-D

