A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Project 646017, Space Systems Command (SSC) Developmental Information Technology Infrastructure (DITI) provides support to enterprise cybersecurity integration,
cyber capability development, and vulnerability management across SSC program offices. The project provides program offices support through Authorizing Official
(AO) and Risk Management Framework (RMF) cyber assessment team, Zero Trust (ZT), cryptography program alignment, data and information availability, Program
Protection, supply chain risk management capabilities, Artificial Intelligence (AI) and secure software management.

 DITI develops and implements cybersecurity tools, processes and policies through multiple efforts. Key efforts include: Authorization to Operate (ATO), development
 of ZT strategies and architectures for legacy and future space systems; building a central repository to track cryptography requirements and associated risks; and
 synthesizing cybersecurity regulations and directives to improve standardization across mission sets.

 Project's efforts focus on developmental cybersecurity and support generation and alignment of cybersecurity policy and guidance, cyber resiliency capability
 development, vulnerability management, data accessibility with automation, and program protection. DITI helps assess technical risks that operational users experience
 in SSC program offices or encounter by understanding the System and Enterprise-level risks posed by threats based on deployment and gathered feedback across
 SSC. Cybersecurity regulation and directives are synthesized, deconstructed, and applied to best determine implementation and standardization across various
 functions and mission sets. Capability development efforts include implementation of DoW cybersecurity policies and guidance such as DoW's Cyber Strategy, ZT
 Strategy, and capabilities. This includes efforts for enabling ZT capabilities in Space Systems and implementation of SSC ZT Guidance and Policy via pilot programs for
 both legacy and future ground and space systems in accordance with Executive Order 14028, "Improving the Nation's Cybersecurity,”, which requires federal agencies
 to establish plans to drive adoption of ZT Architecture. The projects pursued for ZT keeps pace with increasing cyber threats to modernize existing infrastructure into
 SSC programs for mitigation against existing and future vulnerabilities. DITI Developmental Cybersecurity effort will deploy and enhance SSC Supply Chain Risk
 Management (SCRM) capabilities through development of SCRM AI/ML tools that will illuminate and monitor the space defense industrial base and provide real-time risk
 analysis to SSC Program Executive Offices (PEOs).

 Program Protection effort develops databases, tools, and processes to organize information, reduce program-level redundancies to clarify and update user guides,
 policy, and contract language to mitigate foreign threats and commercial risks to SSC programs. The effort also develops agile information access and authentication
 capabilities for the space operations environment to ensure information availability to combat against degradation and disruption.

 The project includes the function of the Command Data and AI Officer (CDAO) which produces and defines architectures for Data and AI. This provides context and
 governance for human machine teaming, and support for operations in the information environment, which is a key consideration in acquisition planning. The CDAO


